    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay that makes sense. so like, who actually holds onto the money in the meantime? is it the realtor or is it someone else? and is it safe like, can someone just grab it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The money isn't held by your realtor personally; instead, it sits in a specialized bank account managed by a licensed escrow agent or attorney, which acts as a neutral third party. This setup is incredibly safe because the funds are segregated from the agent's personal finances and are legally protected, meaning no one can just \"grab\" them without a court order or a completed closing agreement. If the deal falls through, the money is returned to the buyer, and if the sale goes through, it's transferred to the seller, all under strict supervision.\n\nIt's a bit like a very strict, unbreakable vault that only opens when the keys (documents) are all in order and the guards (legal requirements) say it's time. You can trust the system because the law holds the escrow agent accountable for every penny, ensuring that only authorized parties can access the funds.",
