    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "so if the agent is like the guard, what happens if there's like a dispute or something goes wrong with the paperwork? like, how do they decide who gets the money if things get messy?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If the paperwork gets messy or a dispute arises, the escrow agent acts as a neutral referee who simply holds the funds until the parties agree on a resolution or a court order is issued. They cannot decide who gets the money unilaterally; their role is strictly to follow the written contract and the specific instructions left by the buyer and seller. If the deal collapses due to a dispute, the funds are usually returned to the buyer, minus any legitimate fees, while the seller is left without the house.\n\nIn Toronto, this process is often overseen by an attorney or a licensed title company who ensures that all legal requirements are met before any money changes hands. It's a very structured system designed so that no one can steal the money or force the other party into a bad deal. The entire process is documented, and if things go wrong, you can appeal to the court or regulatory bodies to intervene.\n\nJust remember that while the agent is neutral, the outcome depends entirely on which side has the stronger legal case or evidence. If you have concerns about a specific clause, it's best to review the contract with your own lawyer before signing.",
